Healthcare workers at Dr George Mukhari Academic Hospital, north of Pretoria, say they're afraid of being infected with COVID-19 and fear for those close to them eNCA's Nqobile Madlala reports. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Nurses at the Dr George Mukhari Academic Hospital, north of Pretoria, say their workplace -- which is meant to protect them -- is being negligent. Healthcare workers at the hospital say they are afraid of being infected with COVID-19 and fear for those close to them. READ: COVID-19 deaths rise to 1,672 This after one of their colleagues died and 15 others tested positive. The nurses say even though they have had to bury their co-worker, her death has brought no change. Only a sign separates a contaminated area from a non-contaminated one. READ: Couple loses COVID-19 battle, leaving behind three children The nurses say since January they have had to work under these dangerous conditions without being fully paid their salaries and that even though they’re in direct contact with COVID-19-positive patients, nurses are not tested. However, the hospital explains otherwise. "We test as many as we can. I think as of now we have tested an access of 600 of our staff," said Dr Richard Lebethe, CEO at Dr George Mukhari Academic Hospital. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.